inoma with a KRAS G12C mutation and high PD-L1 expression.  This is an aggressive disease requiring prompt and comprehensive treatment.\n\n\n### 5.2 Treatment Recommendations:\n\nFirst-line treatment should be combination therapy with a KRAS G12C inhibitor and a PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitor.  Close monitoring for treatment-related toxicities and adjustment of therapy as needed are crucial.  Formal ECOG performance status assessment is required.\n\n\n### 5.3 Risk Stratification:\n\nHigh risk due to advanced stage, comorbidities, and smoking history.  Formal ECOG performance status will further refine risk stratification.\n\n\n### 5.4 Special Considerations:\n\n* Close monitoring of comorbidities (diabetes, hypertension).\n* Careful consideration of potential drug interactions.\n* Dose adjustments may be necessary based on toxicity and performance status.\n* Supportive care to manage treatment-related side effects.\n* Shared decision-making with the patient and her family.\n* Consideration of clinical trial enrollment.\n\n\n### 5.5 Follow-up Recommendations:\n\n* Regular monitoring of disease response (imaging, blood tests).\n* Assessment of treatment-related toxicities.\n* Adjustment of treatment based on response and tolerance.\n* Supportive care as needed.\n* Regular assessment of quality of life.\n* Multidisciplinary team follow-up.\n\n**Disclaimer:** This assessment is based on the available data and represents a preliminary opinion.  A comprehensive multidisciplinary team (MDT) meeting is essential to finalize the treatment plan.  The recommendations are subject to change based on further clinical findings and the patient's preferences.",
