s:** Primary lesion: 3.8 x 3.2 cm.  Lymph node involvement is multifocal within the right hilar and mediastinal regions.  Precise measurements of involved lymph nodes are not provided but are clearly evident and significant.\n\n* **Progression Criteria:**  The absence of prior imaging precludes a definitive assessment of disease progression.\n\n\n**4. Anatomical Considerations:**\n\nThe primary lesion is located in the right upper lobe, close to the hilum.  The involvement of hilar and mediastinal lymph nodes suggests direct extension or lymphatic spread of the cancer.  The relationship of the tumour to major vessels and bronchi needs further clarification with potentially higher resolution imaging.\n\n**5. Recommendations for Additional Imaging if Needed:**\n\n* **High-resolution CT chest:** To better delineate the relationship of the primary tumor to the surrounding structures (major vessels, bronchi), and to better characterize the extent of lymph node involvement.\n* **MRI Chest:** May be considered to further characterize the primary tumor and assess for invasion of adjacent structures, particularly if surgical resection is being considered.\n* **Endobronchial Ultrasound (EBUS) or Mediastinoscopy:**  These invasive procedures are crucial for definitive staging of mediastinal lymph nodes, particularly for guiding treatment decisions.  While imaging strongly suggests N2 disease, tissue confirmation is essential.\n* **Further imaging of the right supraclavicular lymphadenopathy:**  Ultrasound-guided fine-needle aspiration (FNA) or biopsy of the supraclavicular lymph node is recommended.\n\n\n**6. Limitations and Uncertainties:**\n\nThis report is based solely on the provided imaging studies and clinical information.  The staging assessment is provisional and may require modification following further investigations, particularly tissue confirmation and assessment of lymph node involvement via EBUS or mediastinoscopy. The absence of baseline imaging limits the assessment of disease progression.  The patient's performance status needs formal evaluation to guide treatment planning.\n\n\n**7.  Metadata:**\n\n* **Patient ID:** MDT2024001\n* **Report Date:** October 26, 2024\n* **Reporting Radiologist:** Imaging Analysis Agent\n* **Imaging Modalities:** Chest X-ray, CT Chest, PET-CT\n\n\n**Disclaimer:** This report is for internal MDT discussion only.  It should not be considered a standalone diagnostic or treatment plan.  A comprehensive multidisciplinary approach involving oncology, pathology, and pulmonology is necessary for optimal patient management.",
