      "markdown_content": "# Pathology Report\n\n## Specimen Details\n- **Type:** Right upper lobe mass biopsy obtained via bronchoscopy.\n- **Adequacy:** Adequate tissue for histological examination and molecular testing was obtained.  The specimen size was sufficient for comprehensive analysis.\n- **Processing notes:** Standard formalin fixation and paraffin embedding were performed.  Sections were stained with hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) for routine histological examination and immunohistochemistry (IHC).  DNA was extracted from a portion of the tissue for molecular testing.\n- **Quality indicators:**  Tissue morphology was well-preserved.  Sufficient high-quality DNA was extracted for molecular analysis, as evidenced by successful amplification in the molecular assays.\n\n\n## Microscopic Findings\n1. **Histological Features**\n   - **Type and grade:**  The biopsy shows features consistent with moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung.  Precise grading requires a larger sample and may be refined after surgical resection (if applicable).  The current assessment is based on the available biopsy material.\n   - **Special features:**  The tumor cells exhibit glandular differentiation, with formation of irregular glands and cribriform patterns.  There is evidence of moderate nuclear atypia and brisk mitotic activity.  Significant lymphovascular invasion is not observed in the limited sample provided.\n   - **Prognostic factors:**  The moderate differentiation suggests a potentially intermediate prognosis.  Further assessment of lymphovascular invasion, perineural invasion, and the extent of resection (if surgical resection is performed) will be necessary for a more precise prognostic assessment.\n\n\n2. **Molecular Results**\n   - **Mutation status:**  KRAS G12C mutation detected.  EGFR, ALK, and ROS1 are wild-type.\n   - **Biomarker levels:** PD-L1 expression is 80%, indicating a high likelihood of response to PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitors.\n   - **Therapeutic targets:** The KRAS G12C mutation is a targetable mutation.  The high PD-L1 expression suggests potential benefit from immunotherapy.\n\n\n## Clinical Implications\n- **Treatment relevance:**  The presence of a KRAS G12C mutation and high PD-L1 expression significantly influences therapeutic options.  Sotorasib or adagrasib (KRAS G12C inhibitors) are potential treatment options.  Furthermore, immunotherapy with a PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitor may be considered, either as monotherapy or in combination with other agents.  The precise treatment approach will be determined by the MDT based on the patient's overall clinical status, performance status, and comorbidities.\n- **Prognostic factors:**  The moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, the presence of N2 nodal involvement (based on imaging), and the KRAS mutation are factors that influence the patient's prognosis.  A more precise prognostic assessment will be possible after complete staging and treatment response evaluation.\n- **Additional testing needs:**  While the current molecular panel is comprehensive for initial therapeutic decision-making, additional testing may be warranted.  This includes comprehensive genomic profiling (CGP) to identify potential additional targetable mutations or genomic alterations that could guide therapy.  Further testing of resected tissue (if surgery is performed) will be invaluable for refining grade and assessing other prognostic features like lymphovascular and perineural invasion.  Mutation testing on lymph node samples, if available, would help in understanding the clonal relationship between the primary tumor and the metastasis.",
