unotherapy is also strong given the high PD-L1 expression.  The decision for combination therapy versus single-agent therapy requires MDT discussion and should be individualized.\n*   **Quality of Evidence:** High-quality evidence from phase III clinical trials supports the use of KRAS G12C inhibitors and PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitors in NSCLC.\n*   **Guideline Sources:**  NCCN Guidelines for Lung Cancer, ASCO guidelines, relevant published clinical trials (specific trial citations would need to be added based on the most up-to-date research at the time of treatment planning).\n\n\n**5. Clinical Trial Considerations:**\n\nGiven the patient's specific characteristics (Stage IIIA NSCLC, KRAS G12C mutation, high PD-L1 expression), eligibility for clinical trials investigating novel therapies or combination regimens should be explored. This should be a part of the MDT discussion.\n\n\n**6. Deviations from Standard Practice:**\n\nThere are no planned deviations from standard practice at this time.  The treatment plan will be individualized based on the MDT discussion and the patient's response to treatment.  Any deviations from standard practice will be carefully documented and justified.\n\n\n**7. Limitations and Uncertainties:**\n\nThe current staging is provisional.  The final pathology report and further assessment of the patient's performance status are crucial for confirming the diagnosis and refining the treatment plan.  Prognostication remains uncertain due to the interplay of various factors including the KRAS mutation, high PD-L1 expression, age, comorbidities, and response to treatment.  The patient should be fully informed about these uncertainties.\n\n**Metadata:**\n\n*   **Date of Guideline Application:** October 26, 2024\n*   **Guideline Agent:** Guideline Agent\n*   **Guideline Sources:** NCCN Guidelines for Lung Cancer, ASCO guidelines (Specific trial citations will be added during MDT discussion)\n\n**Note:** This response provides a framework for guideline-bas