      "markdown_content": "# Pathology Report\n\n## Specimen Details\n- **Type and adequacy:** Right upper lobe mass biopsy.  Specimen deemed adequate for histological and molecular analysis. Sufficient tissue was received for comprehensive evaluation.\n- **Processing notes:** Tissue was processed routinely using formalin fixation and paraffin embedding.  Sections were stained with hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) for histological examination and immunohistochemistry (IHC).  DNA was extracted from a portion of the sample for molecular testing.\n- **Quality indicators:** H&E stained slides showed good tissue morphology and cellular preservation.  DNA extraction yielded sufficient high-quality DNA for molecular testing.\n\n\n## Microscopic Findings\n1. **Histological Features**\n   - **Type and grade:** Moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the lung.  The tumor cells exhibit glandular differentiation with moderate nuclear atypia and evidence of some necrosis.  A precise grading using a standardized system (e.g., Gleason score for prostate cancer is not directly applicable to lung adenocarcinoma; however, the description indicates a moderate differentiation. Further grading might require additional histological analysis.\n   - **Special features:**  Presence of occasional mucin production by tumor cells. No evidence of squamous differentiation or neuroendocrine features was observed.\n   - **Prognostic factors:**  The moderate differentiation suggests an intermediate prognosis, although the precise prognostic implications are dependent on staging and molecular profile. The presence of necrosis suggests a more aggressive phenotype.\n\n\n2. **Molecular Results**\n   - **Mutation status:** KRAS G12C mutation detected. EGFR, ALK, and ROS1 were wild-type (no rearrangement).\n   - **Biomarker levels:** PD-L1 expression of 80% was observed by IHC.\n   - **Therapeutic targets:** The KRAS G12C mutation is a known therapeutic target, and several targeted therapies are available. The high PD-L1 expression suggests potential responsiveness to immune checkpoint inhibitors.\n\n\n## Clinical Implications\n- **Treatment relevance:** The KRAS G12C mutation and high PD-L1 expression strongly influence treatment options.  The patient is a candidate for targeted therapy with a KRAS G12C inhibitor (e.g., sotorasib, adagrasib) and/or immunotherapy with a PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitor (e.g., pembrolizumab, atezolizumab).  The specific choice of therapy will depend on other factors, including the patient's overall health, performance status, and the presence of any other relevant mutations.\n- **Prognostic factors:**  The KRAS G12C mutation is associated with a less favorable prognosis compared to some other lung adenocarcinoma subtypes. However, the high PD-L1 expression may improve the likelihood of response to immunotherapy. The presence of metastatic disease (N2) further impacts prognosis, necessitating a multidisciplinary discussion.\n- **Additional testing needs:**  Given the high PD-L1 expression, additional testing to confirm the PD-L1 status using a standardized assay (e.g., using the FDA-approved companion diagnostic test) is recommended.  Further testing of the tumor for other relevant biomarkers (e.g., microsatellite instability (MSI), tumor mutational burden (TMB)) may be beneficial for guiding treatment and predicting response.  Detailed staging including assessment of the lymph nodes (perhaps by mediastinoscopy or EBUS-TBNA) and brain imaging (MRI) are essential to guide treatment decisions.",
